{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658746"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:55:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:55:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20818"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20818"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96207"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13693"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78927"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11223"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32976"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32978"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96207"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents with fever, weight loss, and abdominal distension. She has marked hepatosplenomegaly with the spleen palpable 8 cm below the costal margin. Laboratory tests show pancytopenia. Bone marrow aspirate reveals macrophages containing intracellular parasites. She recently returned from rural India.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following parasitic infections is most likely responsible for this clinical presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leishmaniasis","Schistosomiasis","Trichinosis","Strongyloidiasis","Toxoplasmosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeishmaniasis\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct diagnosis based on the clinical presentation of hepatosplenomegaly, pancytopenia, fever, and weight loss. The finding of macrophages containing intracellular parasites in the bone marrow is characteristic of visceral leishmaniasis (also known as kala-azar). \u003Cem\u003ELeishmania\u003C/em\u003E species invade and activate macrophages throughout the mononuclear phagocyte system, causing systemic inflammation. The massive splenomegaly (up to 3 kg) is a hallmark feature. The patient\u0027s travel history to India is also consistent with this diagnosis, as the Indian subcontinent is endemic for visceral leishmaniasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxoplasmosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fever and lymphadenopathy but typically does not cause the massive hepatosplenomegaly and pancytopenia seen in this case. \u003Cem\u003EToxoplasma gondii\u003C/em\u003E primarily affects the lymph nodes and central nervous system.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrongyloidiasis\u003C/strong\u003E is a nematode infection that primarily affects the gastrointestinal tract and lungs. It can cause abdominal pain, diarrhea, and pulmonary symptoms but does not typically present with massive hepatosplenomegaly and pancytopenia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrichinosis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by ingestion of \u003Cem\u003ETrichinella\u003C/em\u003E larvae in undercooked meat. It typically presents with myalgia, periorbital edema, and eosinophilia rather than hepatosplenomegaly and pancytopenia.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchistosomiasis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hepatosplenomegaly due to portal hypertension from egg-induced granulomatous inflammation and fibrosis, but it does not typically cause pancytopenia or show intracellular parasites in macrophages.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn advanced leishmaniasis, patients are at risk for life-threatening secondary bacterial infections, hemorrhages due to thrombocytopenia, and kidney complications including immune complex-mediated glomerulonephritis and amyloid deposition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Visceral leishmaniasis is characterized by invasion of macrophages throughout the mononuclear phagocyte system causing hepatosplenomegaly, lymphadenopathy, pancytopenia, fever, and weight loss.","Leishmania species are protozoan parasites that can cause four different types of lesions: visceral, cutaneous, mucocutaneous, and diffuse cutaneous.","Advanced visceral leishmaniasis can lead to life-threatening secondary bacterial infections, hemorrhages due to thrombocytopenia, and kidney complications."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 391-392."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78927"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20818"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78927"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T17:23:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-31T17:25:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13693"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96207"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type"